title: Personal Story (Van Gogh's Starry Night)
author: kaitlin
text: the world comes down to a single sleeping town  in the night beneath the sky.   where some still lie awake in the pain of scars that ache with the loneliness learned of have i.   for somehow,  on my own starry night,  no villagers look at the future's plight,  but,  instead,  sleep thoughtless of how small we are.   all that stay here without a dream of beyond this will never live that dream,  nor grow fond of thier tiniest position,  nor become less tiny: a star.

title: Heart Games
author: kaity
text: fill my ears with beautiful words,   words of laughter and endless sanity.  sanity,  is that even what i have?  what i am? what is the definition of sane? is it being calm,  or is it simply not being insane? i trusted with my whole heart i gave you my heart,  to have,  to hold but you gripped it,   squeezed it   juggled it,   split it in three and did a circus act until it oozed through your fingers  like slimy,  swamp water you thought it was a toy,  silly you so now,  i stand before you  stronger than ever.    i have more confidence now than i did before you.   so i thank you  for your attempts to ruin me because in the  long run,  i gained more than i lost for,  if you opened your eyes once in a while  you would see  that my heart is greater now,   tougher.    you thought you had destroyed me,   but,    still i rise  through the fire   a  phoenix

text: at the big top circus everyone sees,   the happy clown that entertains families,   hardly anyone knows about his secret life,   of causing terror deep in the night,    with white makeup and colored hair,   what should anyone have to fear?  with a bright red squeaky nose shaped like a sphere,   when he meets you it might just be the last sound you hear,    with a plastic smile and colorful clothes,   itâ’s amazing how little people really know,   without a sound without a peep,   the creepy clown watches you as you sleep,   heâ’ll pick you up put you into his tiny car,   and before you know youâ’ll have gone very far,    so avoid the circus  stay away for a while,   but whatever you do,   avoid that smile.

title: ''Imagination''
author: kara
text: ''imagination''  when i awoke one morning,   a lemur sat on my head.  i asked,  ''what are you doing there?''  it looked at me and hurriedly rambled,  â“why are you still sleeping?! thereâ’s something you just have to see!â” i sat up,  startled by the realization that a lemur was perched on my noggin.  â“why are you here so unexpectedly,  strange,  fuzzy creature?â” it said,  â“iâ’ve arrived to bring you this wish in a bottle. â” he handed me a sparkling,  golden bottle and popped off the cap.  i gasped! inside was a wish so extraordinary,  iâ’d never seen another like it.  it floated out and swished to the marble floor.  in my head i heard an imaginary choir of hark angels singing about its loveliness.  â“what is the wish?â” i commanded my furry friend.  â“itâ’s your wish,  come true. â” and the thought of my previous wish lit a bulb in my brain.  it was my wish to have an imagination; one that can stretch to the ends of the earth and back.

title: Pure Joy

text: i saw him he saw me he stopped in the middle of the road we stood and stared at each other he said something i couldnâ’t hear i didnâ’t know what i was doing but i took a step toward him he spread out his arms as if beckoning me  to come nearer i took a step back his face flushed  with sadness i took another step back dead autumn leaves blew between him and i a quiet,  whistling wind i looked at him he looked at me i looked into his eyes his red,   fire-like eyes all i felt was love like i was the only creation on this earth that he cared for then i looked again this time at hs around my back facing him  and ran i donâ’t know why maybe it was because i hated him or because i didnâ’t understand why or because he wouldnâ’t give me the answers  that i wanted but i ran i stopped looked back at him he still looked like he glowed in the bright moonlight  his arms still stretched open  his eyes still red and loving and still staring at me i ran i ran as far as i could away from him i looked back he never followed i looked around and realized  i was home i didnâ’t want to be there so i ran i  ran away away from him  away from them i ran i stopped and sat under a willow tree i cried my tears forming a small puddle at my feet wind rustling quietley through the branches of the great willow tree it was then that i realized how much i really needed him i need him i ran back hoping he would still be there that he never left me but when i got back to where i first saw him he was still there right where he was  when i left arms still stretched out waiting for me eyes still set on me loving me feet still glowing glowing for me i took a step closer he said something i could barely hear it while his eyes were still set on me i took a step towards him  my eyes set  set on him he still loved me the same way he did when i first saw him i ran to him i stopped right in front of him he smiled he wrapped his arms around me  i wrapped my arms around him he laughed not an evil laugh but a joyful laugh i buried my face in his chest and cried i told him why i told him i was sorry he took my face in his hands his soft,   perfect hands enclosed around my face they were like a blanket  to me  on a cold winter night i got a shiver that runs up my spine he said â“come to me my child. â” i nodded i really meant to say yes but the words couldnâ’t escape my mouth  he laughed again a pure joyful laugh  he danced he danced around me he danced up and down the street he laughed he jumped he sang he leapt he flew he danced i fell to my knees crying,   laughing joy pure joy thatâ’s how i describe it but no one could know the kind of joy i felt  unless they did the same i looked up into the bright sunrise and saw angels angels dancing,  singing,   leaping everywhere celebrating joy  pure joy

title: Oh Joy To The Morning!
author: kat
text: morning strikes the gloomy darkness to shower it with golden sunrays and annihilate the black monster that is night; the proud oak stands in the sea of swaying daffodils as she welcomes the sun with open branches and gladly embraces his light.  the thrush says good day to the weary tawny owl as he yawns and closes his lamp-like eyes for an undisturbed sleep; like new do the flowers spring from their lament and stand to attention so the sun may behold these bold soldiers that through the night did weep.  in the morning.   oh joy to the sun,  the shimmering sun,  that wakes us from slumber to play,  oh joy to the morning,  the magnificent morning,  that gently announces the day.   the rabbit scuttles from deep in her burrow and munches on grass with a contented ease that can only be found in the day; the excited clouds dart about blissfully reaching out with their forked fingers to stroke the sunâ’s warm face smiling down on the sandy bay.   the bay where the hippo basks in the glistening shallow water,  with the colourful,  tropical reefs and the placid angelfish; where the rain never pauses to consider splashing down and covering the hot sand and the sun absorbing creatures,  like a death wish.  in the morning.    oh joy to the sun,  the shimmering sun,  that wakes us from slumber to play,   oh joy to the morning,  the magnificent morning,  that gently announces the day.   cuddling in shade of the lanky willow the fox cubs eagerly suckle from their willing mother with no objection as such,  nearby the cheerful rabbit sneaks quietly towards her burrow,  making a rapid dash at a yard to avoid the vixenâ’s clutch.  a scream of laughter erupts from a clearing,  high pitched,  exhilirated like no other sound possible within the wood,  the riverside cottage has awoken children flee from the door chasing and laughing,  playing with imagination only children could.  in the morning.   oh joy to the sun,  the shimmering sun,  that wakes us from slumber to play,  oh joy to the morning,  the magnificent morning,  that gently announces the day.  oh joy to the creatures,  the capering creatures,  that scuttle and suckle and play,  oh joy the creatures,  the capering creatures,  that make it a worth while day.

title: Perfect World
author: kate
text: in a perfect world… our hair falls just the right way,  our clothes fit perfectly everyday.  we find our love at the perfect age,  we arenâ’t locked up inside of a cage.  we know who we are,  true friends arenâ’t that far.  but we donâ’t live in a perfect world.  thatâ’s why we live curled,  curled up in a ball,  trying to hide from it all.  terrified of the light,  it truly gives us a fright.  our souls are tormented,  the door to our heart is thoroughly cemented.  you never know whom you can trust,  but we all have this strong lust,  the lust to manipulate and steal,  when all we want is a little feel.  nobody cares about our feelings,  if only you cared about my feelings.

title: My Sublime Phone

title: Beach Trip

title: Just Imagine...
author: katherine
text: a person without a brain,  a sky without a plane.   a ball without a bounce,  a cup without an ounce.   an apple without a core,  a house without a door.   a shoe without a sock,  a boat without a dock.   a phone without a ring,  a bell without a ding.   a pen without some ink,  a dish without a sink.   a dog without a bark,  a night without dark.   a needle without thread,  a blanket without a bed.   a song without a tune,  a fork without a spoon.   a cookie without milk,  a snuggle without a quilt.   a track without a train,  a grandpa without a cane.   a cigar without smoke,  a can without coke.   a beginning without an end,  is like me without a friend.

title: A day

title: The Tree Across the Street From Me
author: kathleen
text: the night seems cold and lonely,  but i see many around me.  across the street from me i see a tree that i find interesting.  the trunk is thick and quite well displayed with the color of slight brown and gray.  the tree lays leafless from winter's best,  but still looks beautiful none the less.  the branches of the leafless tree are entwined  that looks so wild and natural in my subconscious mind.  this tree stands with the companion of two more to make three,   which is more than what i can say about me.  the night seemed cold and lonely,  but the tree across the street from me kept me company.

title: Wearing Long Sleves
author: kathryn
text: as i walk through all the fallen leaves,  i am wearing long sleeves.  they go chunch,  chunch,  chunch.  i go munch,  munch,  munch.  i am eating chips,  as i study about the lunar eclipse.  autumn is so pretty,  and it's like being in the windy city.  autumn is so great,  i hope that you can relate.  walking through the leaves,  wearing long sleeves.

title: Dream
author: kathryn
text: i dream every day through morning and in the night sky.   i think that if i dream  then one day it will become a reality.    but the more that i do,   i just become more disappointed.   so now i have woken up  and no longer focus on what won't happen.   and i am glad that i did  because reality is much more beautiful,   when you let fate take its course.

title: My Bunny
author: katrina
text: one morning early and bright,  i caught a bunny, and he looked quite nice.  i put him in a cage to hold him awhile,  he put a hand on his hip just for style.  when he's hungry he would say,  ''a-oo-a-tis, '' i would feed him,  and look at this: i take him to the brook and the water he took,  my friends want to come and take a look.  they hold him up high,  and he looks so shy,  that i turn my face and sigh.  they put him on the ground,  and he hops all around.

title: What Families Are For
author: katrina
text: what are families for? to lift you when you fall,  to be there when you call,  to teach everything to you,  when you don't know what to do.  to tell you when you're right or wrong,  to sing the sweetest songs,  to fill your heart with love,  they're as gentle as doves.  families,  that's what they are for.

title: The Sun
author: katrina
text: over the trees,  up in the sky,  is a golden ray of bright sunshine.  drying up rain,  and hoping it won't come again.  shining radiantly - that's the sun,  helping children play and have fun.  melting away the winters snow,  making sure the trees and flowers grow.  rising in the east,  setting in the west,  yet it does not even rest.   quietly sitting warming birds' nests,  these are the things the sun does best!

title: In a Dream That Will Never Come True
author: katrina
text: in a dream that will never come true,  the grass is always green and you'll like the birds too! daffodils and dandelions dot the fresh green grass,  up on a pony comes a beautiful young lass.  the scent of pretty yellow flowers fills the fresh air,   and the thing about it too is that life i always fair.  in a dream that will never come true,   the streams and rivulets are always blue,  the fish of many colors swim side by side,   and their bright clear eyes beam with pride.  at night in camp,  if you are lying next to a bear,  you would not even feel scared.  in a dream that will never come true,  you are awakened by a cock-a-doodle-doo! there are no disasters or mishaps,  and the dainty little girls sit on their mothers laps.  it's sunny and breezy everyday,   and everyone is cheerful and nice.   you live in a world of ''i love you'',  in a dream that will never come true.

title: ''Rainbow World''
author: katrina
text: up in the sky,  where the rainbow lies,  little ones play,  their hearts light with laughter.  they run and shout,  and eat sweets of all sorts,  with sticks as sceptors,  they act like royalty in the courts! in the warm zephyrs which make the grass quiver,   they parodize snakes and in the tall grass they hiss and slither.  they play and as they grow,  images blur,   until all is nothing; as adults are they stirred.  they realize all was a small child's game,  and they can never return to the ''rainbow world'' again!

title: I Wish . . . .
author: katrina
text: i wish i were outside playing with all my friends,  i wish my picture would stop falling so i won't have to tape it on the wall again.  i wish i had all the toys i wanted so playing would never ever stop,  i wish i weren't doing my homework,  just sucking a big lollipop.  i wish i were on vacation strolling along the beach,   i wish one of my favorite bathing suits wasn't destroyed by bleach.  i wish the sky were always blue,  the sun high overhead,  i wish the air always smelled like tulips or roses instead.  i wish i didn't have to wake up early in the morning to go to school,  i wish it were never too hot or too cold,  just cool.  i wish my brother were a baby so i could kiss his cut face all the time,  but i can't do it now he's nine - to him it's a crime! i wish nothing was hard in life - it was as easy as blinking,  life is as hard as an unlearned swimmer not sinking.  i wish all these things would come true,  but i doubt that would ever happen,  and i forgot - i wish someday to learn latin.  i wish this poem would end and that's one thing i have the power to do,  so abra-ka-dabra and poof!

title: There's A Warm Feeling in My Home
author: katrina
text: i step inside my living room that's unusually warm,  i sniff the air,  mom's not cooking,  and there's definitely no storm.  dad doesn't have on the heat,  even though it's fall,  i don't have on winter clothes - no,  not at all.  i asked my brother to touch me,  he said that i was cold,  ''then why am i so hot?'' i asked putting my arms in a fold.  ''we all feel warm because there's a lot of love in our hearts, ''  ''that's a pretty good solution, '' i said,  ''and very smart. '' i was calmer knowing why i felt so warm,  even though mom wasn't cooking and definitely there was no storm.  although dad did not have on the heat even though it was fall,  and i did not have on any winter clothes - no,  not at all! at first i would admit i was scared yet cross,  something inside me was burning like hot sauce.  it's hard for me to believe it was love,  because hot sauce isn't as gentle as a dove.  but the solution made me feel much better and i stayed warm,  and now i know it was love,  not cooking or a storm.

title: Good Times with Mother
author: katrina
text: sitting by the fire,  on my mother's lap,  although it's very late,  i'm not tired because i had a nap.  she's telling me a story,  one i've never heard,  about a prince and a princess and something they earned.  the story seems fantastic as far as i can see,  because what the prince and princess earned was me! walking down a pleasant street,  holding mother's hand,  i'm ever so excited,  she's buying me something grand.  every time we pass a store,  my heart starts beating really fast,  and in my mind i'm thinking, ''are we at the store at last?'' finally she stops at an icecream store,  she buys me a banana split,  the flavor i adore.  sitting in the park,  listening to one of mother's songs,  her songs are very soothing,  but this one's a little long.  i tell my mother i'm tired and i would like to go home,  she smiles,  gets up,  and sings a song about being alone.  that night she reminds me of when i used to creep,  then she tucks me into bed and tells me to have a sweet sleep.

title: Night
author: katrina
text: when the sun sets,  and before dawn,  and the dew falls on the front lawn,  when you're fast asleep,  when the stairs creak,   when your house is dark,  without a spark,  when the stars are up in the sky,  and the moon is so bright - oh my! when they say ghosts and monsters hide under your bed,  and you wake up with a scream and tell your parents what they said,  when all the scary beings come out and fill you with fright,  this is night!

title: ''Grow Flower, Grow''
author: katrina
text: in a green lawn,  i find a seed,   as small as a dot- so delicate- i think i shall bring this little thing to life indeed.   i pile the richest soil i can find in a pink flower pot,   gently i place the seed in a suitable spot.   after carefully covering it with a blanket of damp soil, i put the pot by the window.   as the days go by,  through watering and pleasant sunshine,  i gently speak:''grow flower,  grow. '' soon enough,  i can see an iota of green,   it struggles through the dirt- so delicate,  so weak!  i sprinkle it with water making sure it will not drown,   i feed it rays of sunshine patting smooth the damp ground.   as days of anticipation hurriedly pass me by,   encouraging me to have faith and know,   as i sit by the window i gently whisper,  audible to only my friend:''grow flower,  grow. '' and when the pretty buds start to sprout,  and when the colorful petals stretch their bodies out,   oh what joy i feel,  when getting such a substantial success out of a tiny seed! as my friend sprouts taller and taller whilst i sit by the sunny window,   i quietly,  gently whisper:''grow flower,  grow. ''

title: The Proud Old Broom
author: katrina
text: in a dusty room,   stands a dusty broom,  who is given the dirtiest jobs to his own doom.  ''why do they make you do that?'' asked the clean vacuum,  who stood in a clean new room.  ''how should i know why?''  the old broom sighed.   ''you're old and fit for the garbage,  but instead you're kept in storage. ''  ''how dare they do that to me! i was better than all brooms,  didn't you see?''  ''oh,  yes,  you thought you were better than everyone else,   but you never knew you would be in storage yourself!''

title: When I Go to the Meadow
author: katrina
text: when i go to the meadow,  i lie down in the grass,  i'm tired and weary,  i've finished my chores at last! roses and flowers encircle me,  two feet away comes a bumblebee.  i rise and skip to the lake,  it always stays clear for my sake.  the beautiful sunset reflects on the surface,  this brings me much comfort and solace.  when i go to the meadow,  i see pretty butterflies up high,  and they look like designed hearts as they flutter side by side.  a shady tree is nearby,  i sit under it for a while.  its leaves are a shady green,  just right for a picture scene.  the meadow is where i spend my spare time,  a pleasant place to stay away from misfortune or crime.

title: The Color Green
author: katrina
text: when i think of the color green,  i'm not thinking of something mean.  green is one of the colors of spring,  green is something joy brings.  it makes me happy when i think of green,  it makes me think of a stunning picture of string beans! green is on the trees and on the ground,  green is wherever you look around.  green is one of the colors i take to heart,  and i think liking green is a perfect start!

title: The Orphan's Stars
author: katrina
text: when i lived in the orphanage,  i thought of myself wandering on earth,  and when i looked in the sky,  i would wonder what the bright stars are.  i thought i would wander,  to the end of the earth,  but now i know what stars are for,  to brighten up a darkened world.  now that you came,  i don't want you to go away.  what would i do,  without a mom and dad like you!

title: A Rat
author: katrina
text: i saw a rat,  he ate like a brat.  he took my cheese,  and he didn't sat please.  i got so mad,  and he looked so sad,  that he said sorry,  and scurried away in a hurry.

title: Sitting by Crystal Lake
author: katrina
text: bringing my lanyard and a book with me from home,  i'm going to crystal lake where i spend my time alone.   with no one to bother me,  no noise in my ears,  i really like it at crystal lake and i love the fresh air.  i can sit down under the shady trees and sing with the birds,  i make friends with the rabbits by giving them carrots and rubbing their fur.  sometimes i carry my fishing pole and i try to catch fish,  but i never caught enough to make a delicious dish.  crystal lake is a piece of land i can call my own,   crystal lake is a place only a few people have known.  i keep it a secret so i would have it all to myself,  and when my parents ask me, ''where are you going?'' i say, ''near mr.  helft. '' i've been going to crystal lake since i was seven,  and to me crystal lake is a slice of heaven!

title: Fallen Angels
author: kavidini
text: as i watch speechless in wonder,  the glowing angel pauses to ponder in curious glances in amazed surprise on all of godâ’s creations before her angel eyes.   she wonders how these simple beings think how they can act  and be one who seems to have no worries,  no care,  no troubles in the world,  just one in a million of those standing there lost in the crowd mixed in the scene coming and going whenever they please.   do they not care? donâ’t they despair? for being seen as a shell someone who isnâ’t really there.  how do they feel? how do they think? when someone tells them who they are isnâ’t worth anything?  ''what curious creatures, '' the angel says sadly to accept such a fate so eager and gladly.   the angel flutters her wings glancing up as heaven sings beckoning her to return so joy she may bring to the skeletons who walk around without the light of a ring shining sweetly on their heads like the glorious long ago kings   the angel blows a kiss to the earth filled with love and good tidings  of hope that these fallen angels will once again be in a position to accept their wings like the long ago angelic,  glorious medieval kings.

title: The Koala
author: kayla
text: when theyâ’re born,  hairless and pink,  theyâ’re about 8 inches long.  theyâ’re so very small,  not very tall,  and so i will write this song.  using its fore limbs it crawls right out into its mothers pouch while inside,  it is protected,  never will it say ouch! for five months it will stay inside,  preparing to emerge once more.  it will climb out just as if it were going through an open door.  to its motherâ’s pouch it clings,  holding on with claws when it gets a little older,  it will climb through trees using paws.  very soon the day will come after with mom for one year it will move to a separate tree not far but very near.

title: Hatred
author: kelly
text: crimson red pours from a gaping wound slashed by the unhappy,  fragile hate like glass it appears it never would break but now it lays shattered in pieces before me a soul made of glass hatred,  reflecting itself scheming and jealous of the innocent heart and just like the sky it had fallen apart the sharp blue rains down and bloodies my eyes sprung from the shadow,  and feeds off the dark the black tearing and ripping away  it always ligers and not driven by day but greedily gathers and stashes the sun it breathes into fire and turns it to dust beckons with a creeping finger and black nail and smiling evilly at lies it regales murmurs,  â“everything can be broken. â”  eyes raised to the slumping figure on the cross farewell to sinners and saints of the church an empty answer to the core of the search for solutions to questions with no explanation  hate appears even in the dictatorâ’s eyes these men who have pledged their lives to good and they wonder in fear if confronted they would or admit to the darkness and the impure inside shadow makes its way across sapphire seas spreading its arms across all continents gripping the small earth,  already bent and squeezes until there is no breath left the laugh echoes to the far corners of time the world wishes in horror that it was delusion strong ties break away into chaotic confusion and it fades from the earth into the darkness turns from the horizon to the still,  watchful moon quiet and dead in silent wisdom  watches the sad world as it comes undone and the hatred thatâ’s come to claim the earthâ’s teacher and claim it hate does  break the moon,  once so strong and weeping venus wonders what could have gone wrong as it devours mercury and the already gray sun it moves on,  laughing,  consuming the planets and darkens the galaxies the universe cries out,  its inability to see blinded by the hate that started in one heart.   unhappy hate,  fragile at its core and yet in its cruel,  slitted eyes  shows weakness,  and its ultimate demise as it twists its own fingers around its own throat.

title: Jellybeans Rule!
author: kelsey
text: almost every afternoon,  i eat jellybeans with a spoon,  every evening right at six,  i eat jellybeans stacked on bricks,  i like jellybeans on my cake,  i even jellybeans on a lake.   every single time i cry,  i feel like eating jellybeans people would call me a bean fry.  i eat my jellybeans on my fries with ketchup  i even eat a hot sandwich and never clean my mess up,  there are jellybeans on the floor  there are jellybeans everywhere.   every day at lunch  i get a hunch,  people are always watching me eat my jellybeans,  i know they want to eat some because they are just so delicious,  licorice,  grape,  lemon,  oh honey,  oh i love jellybeans so much that i usually waste all my money,  so many pretty colors and flavors,  iâ’m surprised they havenâ’t come out with jellybeans full of flavors.   i wish i could say that jellybeans are in my house constantly but when they are not,  i just go plain crazy! my favorite color i would have to say is midnight blue  so since i love jellybeans so much,  i will make some that are blue! cotton candy flavored jellybeans,  the best flavor ever!  you may think i am crazy for saying this but you will love jellybeans too.  try a taste and you wont think they are a waste! jellybeans are so cool.  say i am a freak,  but jellybeans have definitely have the beat,  they can make you rise in heat!

title: The Blue Moon
author: kelsey
text: the blue moon broke the horizon on a dark night  the night was as quiet and still as the ocean water tickling my skin a blue fish came up to me and i touched its fin,  it swam away,  just like my light,  just like my day.   i only have left the blue moon and the dark sky as my hero the blue moon is like the trees,  they are always moving,  but they are never going away,  my blue moon please donâ’t fade away.  blue moon you have to stay.   the shameless people who tell you lies,  well now no more can they cry.  they only do it to you because they think they can toss people around  treat them like old raggedy shoes.  i say not to,  youâ’re my moon.  oh my blue shiny moon.   please do not cry for what they have done,  it is only jealousy for which they cannot ever over come.  those mistakes they have made and the great shame they obtain they think that have you hanging on a thread well for which they are dead.   have faith in yourself for all thatâ’s needed little blue moon,  for you will try again and succeed like you always do.  you never let me down,  they hate me because i have somebody like you.  frail and limber is what they mistake you as,  the dark figure in the sky when you are scared,  you are the light in my eyes when you are there.   so dream big little moon and keep on shining away,  maybe one day they will realize that their jealousy have to fade away,  especially the smiles they pre-take,  they are so weak that you can see what they have to say.  they are nothing….

title: Love
author: kelsey
text: love is as soft as a snow,  white dove,  it comforts like the rain.    when you hurt and when you cry,    it's there to heal your pain.   love is like a roller coaster,   up and down it goes.    sometimes it takes your friends,  sometimes it takes yours foes.     love is very critical,   you need it to survive.    when you reach out and love another,  you'll feel very much alive.   love affects everyone,   from north to south you see.    love applies to everything,   not just you and me.   love is very delicate,   don't treat it like a toy.    love is a special partnership,   between a girl and boy.   i feel love everyday,   i hope you do as well.    when you do you'll understand,   love-you cannot sell.

title: Possibilities

author: kendra
text: three years ago,  i walked into a pet store.  birds chirping,  cats meowing,  dogs barking.  little did i know,  i'd be walking out with something that would change my life permanently,  curly,  my guinea pig.   it's been 5 months,  5 long,  lonely months,  since i've seen the most precious creature that's ever belonged to me.  his radiant colours,  black,  white,  and gold.  long,  soft fur that you could stroke for days on end.  a personality of his own,  gentle,  understanding,  and loving.  my true lifesaver.   but never,  will i ever,  forget that september morning,  my little brother racing into my room,  waking me up.  i only remember hearing the words,  kendra.

title: Life
author: keshna
text: april 18,  2002   life was never made to be easy.  there are things that keep you wondering like what would happen next.  itâ’s like a puzzle with thousands of pieces,  that has different shapes and sizes.  there are many problems that you come across.  and they never seem to have a solution.  itâ’s like a really big blur like a story with no conclusion.   though life isnâ’t easy there are many rewards.  it might not be money,  but it might be your life.  there are many things youâ’ll come across.  you may meet new people.  life has variable things,  in fact,  life is variable its self.  you should make a lot of it.  be sure to take life seriously.   life has many lessons to learn.  they could be harder than you think.  they become harder and harder,  and your mind,  spirit and soul,  become wiser,  and stronger.  be careful with your actions,  for your actions take a big part.   as the saying goes,  what goes around,   must come back around.  or the saying,  do unto others,  as you would like to be done unto yourself.    life is an important gift,  and that is for everyone.  cherish your life,  because when you were born,  you were and still are a precious baby.   sometimes life can be a burden,  but it is also a wonderful sight.   cherish it,  and it will always seem wonderful,   to you and to others.

title: Where I'm From
author: keyleigh
text: iâ’m from a two-sided mirror,  peering in on who they want me to be,  and knowing who i am by my reflection.  raised by my single mother,  i learned how to be independent.  and from my invisible father,  iâ’ve learned lies and selfishness.   iâ’m from loving god,  and dripping spring baptist.  to john 3:16,  and proverbs 31.  from my pappawâ’s torn bible that he carried everywhere.  from saying â“amenâ” and â“god blessâ” and knowing that he is number one.   iâ’m from fishing off the rusty dock,  to hunting in the sun-kissed fields,  from friday night football,  and that homerun-strikeout baseball.  from texting friends and watching movies,  and where a chevy truck is a manâ’s prized possession.   iâ’m from junie b.  and rotten school,  to william shakespeare and charles dickens.   from the seat to the stage.  to miracles and magic,  from the playground to the pew.   iâ’m from sweet tea and buttery biscuits,  to having that southern sass.  iâ’m from blue capris,  to those stubborn genes,  passed down from generations.   but iâ’m also from broken dreams,  and dad less days.  iâ’m from the rare â“helloâ”,  to the sightless months.  to the other side of the rainbow,  that has no gold or happy ending.   iâ’m from a place where favoritism is favored.  where the slightest flaw,  makes you an outcast.  where people expect too much,  but know too little.   iâ’m from the shadows,  waiting for the glimmer of light,  to take me home.  where i have a father,  who loves me,  and cares for me.  where time doesnâ’t speed up or slow down,  itâ’s still like a sculpture,  now wanting to ruin the masterpiece.   iâ’m from the front of the classroom,  talking away like the wind.  to the straight aâ’s,  i work hard for.  from the school lessons,  that turns into sunday school.   this is where iâ’m from,  although itâ’s not much.  iâ’m not perfect,  and i donâ’t expect to be.  this is my temporary home,  where i was born and raised,  and where my heart will be.  this is where iâ’m from.

title: The Inn
author: kris
text: on that night,  with hope in sight,  a young girl,  named anna,  went her way.  and as she walked,  she sometimes talked of what she was going to do.   ''what in the world, '' she said quietly,  ''was i thinking when,  so happily,  i decided to run far away?'' but still she pressed onward.   now there happened to be at the inn where she rested  a young man of just seventeen.   and when he saw her the butterflies fluttered inside of his stomach,  so lean.   he smiled a crooked smile and said,  ''i wonder what she is like. '' and as he lay in his feathery bed,  he thought about taking her on a hike.   now anna was just a girl of sixteen.  but when she saw with her eyes,  so keen,  the boy the innkeeper called john,  she knew that her troubles were gone.   they met the next day,  while in the garden.  the sight of her made him so happy and gay,  and she was happy to have stayed at the inn.   they walked toward each pother,   and stood side-by-side.  the awkwardness seemed like a cover.  while john  thought of the rules to which he was to abide.   finally anna got tired of waiting and broke the silence with one single question,  ''what is your name? i'm very near dying. '' ''my name is john. '' and so it began.   they later described it as love at first sight,   they met in that spot every night.  'till finally he asked what she wanted most,  ''will you marry me,  anna? my father will host. ''  she was so excited and she said with a smile,  ''this fire's been lighted.  so yes,  i'll walk the mile!''  when the plans had been made,   and the dresses were ordered.  the excitement did not fade or so it was heard.   the bride and the groom  were both very nervous.  they didn't think the room would be filled up unless. . .   ''i will not make the call, '' said john to his bride.  ''fine,  i will call them, '' anna decided.  she dialed the number,  and when he was answering,  she said,  ''hello,  dad.  will you come to my wedding?''  he hung up in anger,  and in relief.  he finally told all of this to his wife.  they made their decision,  only anna could question.   on the day of the wedding,   she looked around quickly.  the moment was drawing,  ever so quickly.   as she walked down the isle she knew this was the beginning of the mile.  she looked at john,  just standing there.  and knew they would be a happy pair.   just as she said the words,  ''i do, '' in waltzed her father,  and mother too.  they waved and then sat,  and anna knew that was that.   and at the reception,  while dancing with john,   her parents asked the question,  ''why did you leave? why did you run?''  anna just smiled,  and so did john.  she looked at them and said,  ''the answer to that,  i cannot discern,  but for that,  i'm glad!''

title: Grandpa
author: kristin
text: you were such a happy guy,  you always had a smile on your face.  i have never seen you upset.  you could always make me laugh,  even though your rhyming was sometimes embarrassing.  why did you have to leave this world so soon? you might have done some pretty weird things,   but i always loved you.  you were the only grandfather i ever knew,  you were the best.  you were always so proud of us grandchildren.  you would always say my beautiful grandchildren,  and my beautiful children.  i know you are in a better place,  but i want you here with me,   so this is my goodbye for now.  i hope to see you in heaven.  i will always treasure and love you.

title: My Thoughts on the Wrong
author: laura
text: i am just a teen,   living in a world of despair.  if you offer me drugs,  i will give a dirty glare.   my friends say i'm shy and that's not a lie,  but when i see no world peace i just want to cry.   abortion makes me gag and wars make me sad,  why do people think we have to be so bad?  bombs keep on flying and people keep on dying.  why can't we make peace? we just keep on fighting!  god loves us all,   and surely will forgive us,  but will we forgive others when they decide to ''diss'' us?  i don't know about you,  or your neighbor or your friend,  but i know one thing i want this violence to end!  i say god bless the world.  god bless the bad.  god bless the people,  who are so often sad.   god bless america.  god bless the sea.  god bless everyone,  including you and me! by.  laura schneider

title: Nine: dog's death
author: lauren
text: she must have been kicked unseen or brushed by a car.   too young to know much,  she was beginning to learn  to use the newspapers spread on the kitchen floor  and to win,  wetting there,  the words,  ''good dog!                                                                     good dog!''  we thought her shy malaise was a shot reaction.   the autopsy disclosed a rupture in her liver.   as we teased her with play,  blood was filling her skin  and her heart was learning to lie down forever.   monday morning,  as the children were noisily fed  and sent to school,  she crawled beneath the youngest's bed.   we found her twisted and limp but still alive.   in the car to the vet's,  on my lap,  she tried  to bite my hand and died.  i stroked her warm fur  and my wife called in a voice imperious with tears.   though surrounded by love that would have upheld her,   nevertheless she sank and,  stiffening,  disappeared.   back home,  we found that in the night her frame,   drawing near to dissolution,  had endured the shame  of diarrhoea and had dragged across the floor  to a newspaper carelessly left there.   good dog.    this poem was not writen by me.  i do not know who the real poet is.  but who ever you are you have touched me very much because this is like the same way my first dog died.

title: Down the Hall

text: down the hall she ran again.  escape the madness if she can.   brothers,  sisters go away,  only to come back again someday.   down the hall she runs again,  to the room with walls of red.   to get away is hard to do,  but some things she just has to do.   down the hall,  for the last time,  '' it's time to go!'' , her mother cries.  down the aisle she walks in white,  away from the hall,  where she ran for the last time.

text: a little girl,  only four,  stands on her fathers feet,  her father sings loudly,  but the girl doesnâ’t make a peep.   happily,  they prance around,  safe is daddyâ’s arms,  feeling comfort that her tiny feet donâ’t have to touch the ground.   daddy is slightly imperfect,  but his daughter cannot see,  his uneven eyes,  his crooked nose,  and his overgrown beard,  but she sees a perfect man,  as she gazes up,  her head only coming to his knee.   daddy is her hero,  the man sheâ’ll always love,  her admiration for her father growing stronger everyday,  when she looks into his eyes,  she sees an angel from above.   when itâ’s time to go to bed,  she tells him something very true,  as he tucks her under her covers and turns off the light,  she whispers,  â“daddy,  i love you. â”

title: Sitting Down To Stand up
author: lily
text: it was a cold snowy day on december 1,  1955 when my world changed unexpectedly i left work and got on the bus.  i took a seat in the section for colored,  not knowing something would happen,  the bus filled up  so the bus driver came back,  moved the segregation  sign a row back,  and demanded me and three others to give up our seats,  the other three gave up their seats and moved,  but i refused  then the bus driver called the police and they took me to the jail,  i didnâ’t know what was going to happen,  i was scared yet almost relieved,  they let me out later that night on bail,  but it didnâ’t stop there.  members of the african american community had been asked to not ride public busses,  they were encouraged to stay home from school and work,  but if they needed to go,  they were asked to walk or take a cab the plan was to hold off on african americans taking the bus up until rosaâ’s trial that was on december 5.  with african americans staying off of the busses it was making such a great impact that they thought to push it out a little longer.  ,   i then realized i didnâ’t move because i was tired i moved because i was tired of giving in and not being treated fairly.   i never expected to make history i was just tired of giving up.   i never thought i would be the one to make a change i didn't realize i had made such a big change  and took such a big risk.  for myself and the community.

title: I'll Never Forget
author: lina
text: i'll never how once i got to meet you,  how once i got to believe that you will be with me this year,  as you said you would be.    i'll never forget how you changed my mood from discouraged to hopeful again,  how you talked to me softly,  how much i wanted to smile now and then.   i'll never forget your voice,  i'll never forget your eyes that even from a thousand miles would shine as bright as the stars in the sky. . .   i'll never forget how you made sure i was doing all right every day,  how much i wanted to cry when you were leaving,  how badly i wanted you to stay. . .   i'll never forget how you took that essay from me,  last assignment i had to turn in,  how you said i will do good,  how you said it was in my power within.   i'll never forget how you made me feel,  how much i depended on you,  and how you took care of me to the best you could.    i'll never forget how you helped me  not to get behind in the class,  how you did everything for me -  what was possible and what was not.   i'll never forget how you smiled at me in the hallway -  the only time when i smiled back. . .  i hoped it would happen many,  many times yet,  but the last one happened that day. . .   i'll never forget how i didn't feel pressure saying goodbye to you every day,   but it was different then,  and i never said the final one i had to say. . .   i'll never forget how i cried in the bathroom right after the bell ended your class,  i should apologize to you for not staying strong -  not only should - i feel like i must.    i'll never forget how many times you had definitely saved my grade,  and i never got to say ''thank you!''  for your fantastic contributions at the end. . .    i'll never forget how you gave us notes that everyone hated - i did not,  every activity was fun with you but it will never be that way anymore. . .    and i'm trying to remember the bright side and the amazing assistant you've been,  but i still miss you terribly,   in my heart you're always with me.

title: I Remember...
author: liz
text: i remember her smile,  that made her look divine,  i remember her tortillas,  and how they'd taste of ham.  i remember how spontaneous she was,  loving,  accepting,  and how fancy she always seemed.  i remember how she wore her hair,  and how it glistened when the sun shone through.  i remember how i loved the fact that she loved to go to the beach just to see the sand.  i remember her willing personality,  with great teacher skills.  she was also a jogger,  and a real patient one too.  i remember her style,  and that angel perfume.  i saw her as the most bravest,  daring person i'd ever met.  even though you didn't see it through.  i remember when i was smaller i used to called her ''mamita, '' and ''mother'' as i got big.  and mamita i will always remember you,  as the most beautiful person ever that i have seen.  so i thank you now for giving me something to remember throughout my life,  i owe it to you,  because i remembered.

text: ode to a perfect game   a 300 game is the aim  at the start of each new game  the first ball is thrown   will my perfect game be blown?   then with a bang,  fell all ten pins one strike down,  now it begins two more balls pitched down the lane hitting the pins like a train  frames 4,  5,  6 pins dropped with the breeze  six strikes in a row donâ’t let me freeze frames 7and 8 gave a little scare the 10 pin shakes but,  i give it a glare  strike number 9 could be heard across the state now on to the 10th frame will it seal my fate? 1,  2,  3 more strikes are down and now i have won the 300 crown  whoo!! yelled the crowd as i fell to a knee could this really be me!! but the score at the end,  says it all my name will be on the 300 wall

title: Brunby's Herd
author: marilee
text: old brumby was a racehorse,  the king of the course.  he ran lap after lap beating even phar lap.   but of course to this happy tale,  thereâ’s a sad and sorry end for brumby one day vanished â‘round the bend and the last we ever saw of him was the tip of his tail.   it lies beyond the western pines towards the sinking sun and not a survey mark defines the bounds of brumbyâ’s run.   he wakes his herd from dawn til dusk theyâ’re never heard and they vanish just after the sun.   you may hear their hoof beats pass thudding in the grass in the trees you hear a whisper and a sway as they vanish far away.   brumby found himself a mate together they ate together they ruled the herd the herd that never says a word.   we found brumby and his mate we found they sired and dammed good racehorses that won the national just as he had done years before.   it seemed like brumby had been born again young and fit and healthy to race and win again he made us wealthy once again.   his offspring proved just as good as he on and off the track several group one wins the triple crown too.   but sadly old brumby passed away we buried him with his saddle his hooves polished and picked atop his favourite hill.

title: Just the Rain
author: megan
text: transparent strings of moisture luminating the starless black sky.  as the drops cling to my eyelashes and drench my body,  i sing to myself.   the beads of water are falling down my forehead and my cheeks as joyful teardrops do.  as i blink my lids just once,  i clear my eyes.   my dark brown hair sticks to my face  and falls down my back.  as i gather wet flowers from the only place they grow,  i remember.   the mud-filled pools of rain in the clean,  wet grass fill my shoes with water.  as i walk along down this field of memories,  i fall.

title: Here I will Dwell No Longer
author: megan
text: i am a princess unlike no other.  here i dwell amungst the chattering woodland creatures,  nobel firs and elms and babbling brooks.   my weightless robes are spun of only the finest spider's silk,  sequenced with dew drops and snowflakes.  on my feet i bear no shoes,  for the creative,  uneven landscape masages them.  a sprinkle of pixie dust in my cascading golden hair radiates my appearance.   alas,  my story has become a sad one.  as it used to be,  i would play with children,  grown men and women.  so long as they were good to me,  i would shine for them,  let them see my true beauty.  yet now,  people are losing sight of me.  i am growing smaller,  weaker with every tree that is destroyed,  every computer that is sold,  i am dying.   take a look around you,  what do you see? you see sky scrapers and industrial plants.  i am becoming sparse amungst so many of your fake landscapes you call cities,  for i am the wind,  the rain,  the snow,  the earth and the wild creatures you consider to be pests.   i am a princess unlike no other.  here i dwell amungst the diminishing woodland creatures,  unhealthy firs and elms and poluted brooks.  soon,  here i will dwell no longer.

title: Pictures on the Wall

title: Veteran's First Battle
author: michela
text: looking out into the vast,  barren land,  the wind whispers into my ears.  we listen to all the general's commands.  sunshine reflects off of all metal in its reach.   my thoughts line up as the soldiers do.  so still,  so focused,  their eyes lead you to their souls.  we line up.  silent,  our commitments are true.  the sparkle of reflected metal now visible in the distance.   the enemy marches,  so perfect and straight.  about a mile away they stop,  no emotion shown.  distantly,  a weapon spins,  then points in our direction.  suddenly a shot was heard,  and hit one of our own.   we shot back,  one of their own gone now.  their blood is our strength.  the eruption of sudden chaos struck,  every minute is another hour. . .   the battle is won,  but the war has no end.  injured soldiers surround me.  not many left,  not much to defend,  they're sending some of us home now.

text: i want to talk to you; but itâ’s like you donâ’t hear me.    i want to talk to you; but itâ’s like you wonâ’t hear me.    i want to talk to you; but itâ’s like you canâ’t hear me.     i want to speak to you; but itâ’s like you donâ’t listen to me.    i want to speak to you; but itâ’s like you wonâ’t listen to me.    i want to speak to you; but itâ’s like you canâ’t listen to me.     i want to explain to you; but itâ’s like you donâ’t understand me.    i want to explain to you; but itâ’s like you wonâ’t understand me.    i want to explain to you; but itâ’s like you canâ’t understand me.     i donâ’t to talk to you; because you donâ’t,  wonâ’t,  and canâ’t hear me.    i donâ’t to speak to you; just because you donâ’t,  wonâ’t,  and canâ’t listen to me.    i donâ’t explain to you; purely because you donâ’t,  wonâ’t,  and canâ’t understand me.     i wonâ’t talk to you; for the simple reason that you donâ’t,  wonâ’t,  and canâ’t hear me.    i wonâ’t speak to you; for the simpler reason that you donâ’t,  wonâ’t,  and canâ’t listen to me.    i wonâ’t explain to you; for the simplest reason that you donâ’t,  wonâ’t,  and canâ’t understand me.    i canâ’t talk to you; since you donâ’t,  wonâ’t,  and canâ’t hear me.    i canâ’t speak to you; since you donâ’t,  wonâ’t,  and canâ’t listen to me.    i canâ’t explain to you; since you donâ’t,  wonâ’t,  and canâ’t understand me.     and now that you want me to talk to you,   to speak to you,   and to explain to you,   it's too late;  i canâ’t talk;   my mouth is stitched shut.

title: My cat
author: naomi
text: i have a cat who loves to play fetch  hes  really no ordinary cat  he loves to eat dog food and loves to chase dogs he loves it when you throw a ball for him to go catch he likes to jump and likes to hide and my o my he loves to hide i guess you can say hes like a dog because my o my he hates thing way to tall he will not climb or scratch or pur all he does is bark play catch thats why i call my cat the dog

title: The creature
author: naomi
text: i looked into the cuboard,  i saw something blue,  it looked like mother hubburd,  but then it said achoo,  it had bright green hair,  and a big red nose,  and then i turned the light on,   but it was just you.

title: Mommy's Mess
author: nashalie
text: she messes up the whole house.  she mess up her hair with the straightener,  she burns it.   she messes up all room looking for her dog.  she messes up her phone trying to get on facebook.  she messes up my eggs trying to cook them different.   the mess that she does is making me crazy.  she tries to clean up the mess but what she does is a big mess

title: Trees
author: natalie
text: green,  yellow,  and brown colors of a changing tree it changes every season,  but it doesn't have a reason  the leaves fall off  and they are left to rot  no matter the color,  people still use it for shade

title: Loving You
author: natalie
text: you said you liked me and she meant nothing to you but the things you both said were so very untrue   i loved you both and meant so much to me but your feelings for each other were so easy to see  i thought you loved me,  i thought you cared  i thought you cherished the moments we shared what she did was so unfair  but so much hurt i had to bear  i thought we would last and be together forever i wont trust her not now not ever my feelings for you i still cant hide  i'll never forget the tears that i cried  my feelings for you are still there  what i feel for you is oh so rare we had our ups and downs,  but i'm still here loving you if only you loved me it'd be such a dream come true
